  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="MuTA47">
<l>niṉṟa perumāṉē nīrēṟ ṟulakellāñ</l>
<l>ceṉṟa perumāṉē ceṅkaṇṇā – vaṉṟu</l>
<l>turakavāy kīṇṭa tuḻāymuṭiyāy naṅka</l>
<l>ṇarakavāy kīṇṭāyu nī</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>O great lord who stood there receiving water, o great lord</l>
<l>who traversed all the worlds, o red-eyed one<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Here the Tamil exploits the pun between kaṇṇaṉ as a proper noun referring to Kṛṣṇa and the one with eyes, as well as: “upright Kaṇṇaṉ!”</note>, you with the tulsi crown</l>
<l>who that day tore apart the mouth of the horse, for us</l>
<l>you also tore apart the mouth of hell.</l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
